{"key":"post-11170020","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11170020</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;anonjon said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Yeah it does.&lt;br /&gt; Soak that long at higher temps and the seeds germinate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You should rinse the grains in hot tap water before the soak to remove dust, chaff, bugs, etc.&amp;nbsp; The scalding hot tap water 'kills' the seeds, preventing germination during the soak.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Soaking longer than 24 hours at room temp can be counterproductive.&amp;nbsp; Many endospores that germinate and grow will produce thousands of new endospores within a few hours.&amp;nbsp; Since some of these nearly always survive pressure cooking, you could easily end up with more bacteria than you started with if you soak too long.&amp;nbsp; I've found after a four to six hour soak, provided it was initiated with hot water, the grains have softened enough to be boiled without bursting the kernels.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>11169123</prev>\n<first>11136386</first>\n<last>11170020</last>\n<when>1254512784</when>\n<utime>10/02/09 10:46 PM</utime>\n</post>"}